  "prompt": "How are passive and active transport different?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between passive and active transport:\n\nPassive Transport:\n1. Does not require energy (ATP)\n2. Moves molecules from high to low concentration\n3. Follows concentration gradient\n4. Molecules move naturally without cellular assistance\n5. Examples include diffusion and osmosis\n6. No protein carriers needed\n\nActive Transport:\n1. Requires energy (ATP)\n2. Can move molecules against concentration gradient\n3. Goes from low to high concentration\n4. Requires protein carriers/pumps\n5. Allows cells to control molecular movement\n6. Examples include sodium-potassium pump and endocytosis\n7. Can concentrate molecules inside or outside the cell\n\nThe main difference is that passive transport follows natural molecular movement, while active transport requires cellular energy to move molecules against their concentration gradient.",
